This paper discusses the phenomenon of Zipf's law of abbreviation in human language and its potential origins. Given that the paper focuses on language and information theory, the most likely sub-category is cs.CL (Computation and Language). Additionally, the paper uses concepts from machine learning and statistics, which could also place it in cs.LG (Machine Learning) or cs.IT (Information Theory). The paper also discusses the relationship between probability and magnitude, which could place it in cs.SI (Social and Information Networks) or cs.CC (Computational Complexity).
